# Comment Style

Comments are allowed, but keep them short and meaningful. Do not be verbose.

- Prefer a single one-line comment over a paragraph.
- Only comment on non-obvious intent, trade-offs, or constraints. Never narrate what the code plainly does.
- Inline (trailing) comments are fine for a short note on a line, e.g. units or a constant's meaning. Keep them brief.
- Method/function headers may use more than one line to describe purpose, params, and behavior.

```c
// ❌ BAD: verbose, narrates the obvious
// This function takes a value, then it increments the counter by one,
// and finally it returns the new value to the caller.
int inc(int x) { return x + 1; }

// ✅ GOOD: one-line, only when it adds meaning
// Clamp to avoid integrator wind-up near saturation
int inc(int x) { return x + 1; }

// ✅ GOOD: short inline note on the line
#define MPU_I2C_TIMEOUT_MS 1   // fail fast, well under one control tick
float dt = 0.002f;             // loop period [s]
```

```c
// ✅ GOOD: multi-line allowed at a method header
// Fuses gyro + accel to estimate tilt angle.
// dt: loop period in seconds; returns angle in radians.
float estimate_tilt(float gyro, float accel, float dt) { ... }
```
